# KBOS Core Architecture

KBOS is a **local-first knowledge OS** over a filesystem vault. Plain Markdown on disk is the **only** authoritative content store.

## Non-negotiable

- Never store authoritative note content in SQL, vector DBs, search indexes, or proprietary formats.
- Everything under `.kb/` is generated cache — disposable. `rm -rf .kb && kb rebuild` must fully recover indexes.
- Encrypted plaintext: decrypt in memory only; never persist plaintext or index it while locked.
- App must remain useful without AI; cloud and Git are optional.
- Users must access all assets via documented open formats + CLI if the UI vanishes.

## Vault layout

```
vault/
├── docs/          # notes (filesystem = UI hierarchy)
├── templates/
├── assets/        # content-addressable attachments
├── config/kb.yaml
└── .kb/           # search, vectors, graph, cache, backups — rebuild only
```

## Content conventions

- CommonMark + GFM + YAML frontmatter (`title`, `tags`, `aliases`, `status`, `created`, `updated`).
- Wiki links: `[[note]]`, `[[path/note]]`; embeds: `![[note]]`, `![[note#Section]]`, `![[note^block]]`.
- Folder landing pages: `index.md` per folder.
- Tags: `#tag` inline and `tags:` in frontmatter.

## Stack (defaults)

| Layer | Choice |
|-------|--------|
| Backend | Go — single binary, strong FS/CLI |
| Frontend | React, Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind, shadcn/ui |
| Search | Bleve — no external search server |
| AI | Provider abstraction (OpenAI-compatible, Ollama, etc.) — optional |

## Before implementing a feature

1. Does it read/write authoritative content only under `docs/`, `templates/`, `assets/`, `config/`?
2. Can derived state be rebuilt from the vault?
3. Does the CLI expose the operation without the web UI?

